### 📊 **Compliance Checklist**

#### RPG Standards (MANDATORY)
- [ ] 100% free-format RPG (no C-spec, D-spec, F-spec fixed format)
- [ ] MAIN or NOMAIN specified on CTL-OPT
- [ ] EXPORT keyword on all procedures in NOMAIN programs
- [ ] MONITOR/ON-ERROR/ENDMON for exception handling (no EXSR/BEGSR)
- [ ] Modern BIFs used (%TRIM, %SCAN, %SUBST, %REPLACE, %CHAR, %DEC)
- [ ] Named indicators only (no numbered indicators like *IN01)
- [ ] QUALIFIED data structures
- [ ] CONST keyword on input parameters
- [ ] LIKEDS, LIKE, EXTNAME used appropriately
- [ ] Proper declaration order (DCL-PR, DCL-PI, DCL-C, DCL-DS, DCL-S)

#### SQL Standards (MANDATORY)
- [ ] SQLCODE/SQLSTATE checked immediately after every SQL statement
- [ ] No WHENEVER clause (strictly prohibited)
- [ ] Set-based operations preferred over row-by-row cursors
- [ ] Cursors properly declared, opened, fetched, and closed
- [ ] Explicit COMMIT or ROLLBACK on all code paths
- [ ] No SELECT * (specific columns listed)
- [ ] Prepared statements for dynamic SQL
- [ ] SQL isolated into procedures (one procedure per SQL action)
- [ ] Cursor names prefixed with program name
- [ ] Handles NOT FOUND (SQLCODE 100) explicitly

#### IBM i Platform (MANDATORY)
- [ ] No hardcoded library names (use *LIBL or qualified references)
- [ ] Proper authority validation before operations
- [ ] Commitment control used for multi-file transactions
- [ ] Timezone-adjusted timestamps (TO0P09FN() function)
- [ ] Resource cleanup in all code paths (including errors)
- [ ] Appropriate activation group settings (DFTACTGRP(*NO))
- [ ] File overrides scoped and cleaned up
- [ ] Message queue handling for errors
- [ ] No assumptions about job type (interactive vs batch)

#### Documentation (MANDATORY)
- [ ] Comprehensive header comments (program purpose, author, date)
- [ ] Parameters documented in header
- [ ] Dependencies listed in header
- [ ] Change log with PIF numbers
- [ ] Modification markers in columns 1-5 for all changes
- [ ] Procedure documentation (DCL-PROC comments)
- [ ] Complex logic explained with inline comments
- [ ] Comments explain "why" not "what"

#### Security & Logging (MANDATORY)
- [ ] No hardcoded credentials or sensitive data
- [ ] Input validation for all user-provided data
- [ ] Logging to UTSP_LOG or approved logging utility
- [ ] No PHI or sensitive data in logs
- [ ] Appropriate log levels (INFO, WARN, ERROR, FATAL)
- [ ] Security-relevant events logged
- [ ] Error messages don't expose system internals

#### Performance (RECOMMENDED)
- [ ] Batch processing where appropriate (not one-by-one)
- [ ] Efficient SQL (appropriate indexes considered)
- [ ] Minimal data transfer (only needed columns)
- [ ] Proper commit frequency (every 1000 records)
- [ ] Avoid unnecessary record locking
- [ ] No SELECT * in production code

#### Project-Specific (If Applicable)
**Price Transparency Phase II:**
- [ ] PATNO + CYCLE join used (both fields required)
- [ ] Primary, Secondary, Tertiary CPT fields checked
- [ ] Modifier column included in PT_MRF operations
- [ ] Discrete (non-interpolated) percentile calculation
- [ ] processed_date used for filtering (not service_date)
- [ ] Denials and zero payments excluded
- [ ] Non-destructive updates (no Phase I modifications)
- [ ] Minimum payment count threshold enforced
- [ ] Formula-specific program structure followed

